By Royal Decree,

Queen Anais Rhindaun and the Royal Council have decreed, any faiths that wish to legally worship within Tethyr are held to the following tenants:

All recognized religions within Tethyr are required to pay tithes to the Crown as well as provide levies in times of need based upon the size of their respective parish.

Worship of an individual deity cannot involve the theft from or the destruction of Tethyrian Citizens.
 - No sacrifice of humans, demi-humans, humanoids, or animals is permitted.

A deity's veneration cannot demand tribute from those outside its faith. The faithful may give offerings as they see fit, but nonbelievers cannot be coerced into doing so.

Harmful activities countenanced by one's religion cannot be practiced upon nonbelievers with impunity.
 - For example, followers of Tempus cannot run amok in the high-lands, wantonly attacking others simply to further the name of the god of battle.

Such religious stipulations may be lifted in times of war, provided the church's religious and moral authority are used against Tethyr's foes.


Endorsed by: Queen Anais Rhindaun and the Royal Council
Royal Decree: Religious Requirements for Legal Worship in Tethyr

Royal Decree: Monterous Races, and Bounty Collection

In Tethyr, the temporal authority on justice in a county is a Magistrate. For all crimes that deal with the common people (Low Justice) the Sheriff has all authorities and rights granted to a Magistrate in the service of Her Crown, including seeing out punishment. For all acts of High Justice, a regional Magistrate must be called in for trial, judgement and sentencing.

Magistrates of any level, whether the position is filled in by an official of the state or by the local Sheriff, are provided this document so it may serve as a foundation for sentencing. The guidelines proposed and maintained in this document are not an absolute or iron-clad ruling and the Magistrate must use their recognizance to determine absolute guilt and innocence as well as set any sentence (or lack thereof) that they consider fitting. If the magistrate finds that the crime committed is justified, innocuous, or inadvertent then there may be cause for leniency at the subject of their own whims.

A Magistrate has the following rights in order to ensure that public justice is served:

The right to seize and confiscate the property of a convicted law-breaker to gain money needed for payments of fines or damages.
a. Families, clans or employers of a convict are not liable for a convict's fines or damages, unless they are also found guilty of aiding, abetting or forcing said convict into the criminal act in question.
b. The seizure of convict's property does not take into account the social status or consent of the convict. A convicted Lord, may have his lands taken.
c. Appraisal of a convict's property is subject to the County Appraiser in order to properly define the number and amount of personal property requires to pay off debts.II. The right to intern any convict within an appropriate holding place or jail for an indefinite amount of time until such time that their punishment's requirements can be met.
a. Local Lords, Garrisons, or Sheriffs are all subject to opening and offering space within their dungeons or cells in order to hold a convict or a potential prisoner.III. Redefine the crimes and punishments associated with a given crime to serve that crime.
a. Final word or a chance of appeal may also lie in the hands of the noble who's land the crime was committed on. (In the case of cross-county or landowner crimes, all nobles.)
b. If this right leads to abuses or injustice against Tethyr, the magistrate or nobles responsible are subject to the whims and punishments of the High Court of her Majesty.
Guidelines for Sentencing:

High Justice: Any severe or serious offense; any crime that results in a sentence of death. An accountable High or Low Justice crime committed by noble defendants.
Low Justice: Any lesser or minor offense. An accountable crime committed by common defendants of the lower or middle class.
Severe Offenses

Crimes Against Crown & Country

Treason - An act against the Crown, her Lands or her People. Includes assault upon a royal person.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Immediate Death (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)

Forgery of an Official Document - The unlawful creation of Writs of Travel, Knighthood, Rank or other documents used by officials of the State to determine the class or identify a person of any social standing.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Mutilation (A branding, or loss of extremities) and Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Permanent Enforced Hard Labor (At a location of the Magistrate's choosing) and Mutilation (A branding, or loss of extremities.)

Assaulting a Noble - The act of physically assaulting a member of the Noble Class, with a weapon, magic or other less savory means.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine of up to 4,000 GP and Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Fine of up to 8,000 GP and Permanent Enforced Hard Labor (At a location of the Magistrate's choosing.)

Assaulting a Magistrate or Sheriff - The act of physically assaulting a servant of the State of Tethyr whether on or off duty.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Up to 10 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Up to 12 years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Spying or Sabotage for a Foreign Power - The willing aid of a Foreign Power in any form or capacity, that the Magistrate finds could or has lead to the death of Tethyrian Citizens.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine of up to 5,000 GP and Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Fine of up to 5,000 GP and Permanent Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing.)
- Fine of up to 5,000 GP and Permanent Exile from Tethyr.
- Fine of up to 5,000 GP and Permanent Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing.)

Crimes against the People

Arson - The act of destroying a ship, structure or stored property of a Lower or Middle Class Citizen of Tethyr through physical, magical or other means.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages with a value of the property lost, plus up to 1,000 GP and up to 6 years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Damages with a value of the property lost, plus up to 1,000 GP and up to 5 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Murder - The act of murdering another Citizen or Resident Alien of Tethyr of Lower or Middle Class. (Punishment for the act of murdering a noble should be guided by "Assaulting a Noble".)
Appropriate Punishment: Any single punishment or a logical combination of -
- Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Minimum of 15-20 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing.)
- Mutilation (A branding, or loss of extremities.)
- Permanent Exile from Tethyr and forfeiture of all rights, lands and property to the State.
- Minimum of 15-20 years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing.)

Assault (Resulting in Mutilation or Crippling) - The act of physically assaulting a member of the Lower or Middle Class, with a weapon, or other less savory means that does not result in death but results in a change in an inability to work their trade.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages of up to 2,000 GP and Mutilation/Crippling (Identical to victim).
- Damages of up to 2,000 GP and 5 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Magical Assault - The act of magically assaulting a member of the Lower or Middle Class with any magical means. Including, but not limited to: The summoning of a creature, the use of a spell to manipulate or control another, any form of spell that harms another. Additional charges may be leveled against the convict based on property damages, murders or other assaults that occur from their magic.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine of up to 1,500 GP, Damages of up to 3,000 GP to any victims, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edicts against the Convicted (including a public pronouncement of guilt and a ban from practicing magic.)
- Fine of up to 1,500 GP, Up to 30 days Enforced Hard Labor (as an Indentured Spellcaster for the State)

Crimes against Religions

Defiling a Holy Place - The act of vandalizing a holy place. Includes burglary, arson or general vandalism.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to what Justice Demands and Permanent Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Damages equal to what Justice Demands and Permanent Exile from Tethyr.

Tomb-Robbing - The act of unlawfully entering or vandalizing a tomb, including burglary.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Up to 20 months Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Damages equal to Cost of Repairs, plus 1,000 GP and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt) and Up to 8 months Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Serious Offenses:

Crimes against Crown & Country

Spying or Sabotage for a Native Power - The willing aid of a Native Power in any form or capacity, that the Magistrate finds could or has lead to the death of Tethyrian Citizens.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Death upon Conviction (at the hands of a Knight, Executioner, or other servant of the State and People.)
- Mutilation (Traitor's Brand) and Up to 40 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Fine equal to Cost of Repair plus Up to 5,000 GP and Up to 40 years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Theft, Vandalism or Arson against Crown or Noble Property - The act of destroying, damaging or stealing any property of either the State or one of the Noble Class.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine equal to the Cost of Repair plus Up to 5,000 GP and Mutilation (A branding, or loss of extremities).

Bribery of a royal officer, court officer, or military official (Attempted or Apprehended) - The act of attempting or succeeding in bribing a State Official.
Appropriate Punishment:
- 10-20 years of Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing) and Confiscation of All Property (Except one weapon, one week's rations, and the offender's clothing worn at the time of sentencing.)

Impersonation of a Magistrate, Sheriff, Royal or Military Officer or other Court Official - The act of attempting or succeeding to impersonate a State Official.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine of up to 5,000 GP, Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and a minimum of 1 year Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Wrongful Seizure or Use of Land - The unlawful seizure of any citizen's land or the unlawful use of a citizen's land.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to the cost of Restoration of the Land and Up to 2,000 GP and Up to 10 years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Fine of up to 2,000 GP and Permanent Exile from Tethyr.

Repetition of any Lesser or Minor Offense against Crown & Country
Appropriate Punishment: (Includes double the original sentence for previous offense)
- Up to 2 Months Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Up to 1 Month Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Crimes against the People

Robbery - The act of taking or trying to take another's property by utilizing intimidation, force or threat. (Victim present.)
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to the Value of Goods Lost plus up to 500 GP, Up to 6 Months Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing)

Burglary - The act of unlawfully entering a structure with the intent to commit theft. (Victim not present.)
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to the Value of Goods Lost plus up to 500 GP, Up to 6 Months Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing). Suggested that internment location be less desirable than just robbery.

Usury - The act of lending money or services at unreasonably high rates of interest.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to excess charged, returned to injured party.

Bribery - The act of attempting or succeeding in bribing any other citizen of Tethyr.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine equal to amount of bribe or attempted bribe and Up To 1 Month Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Forgery - The act of attempting or succeeding in forging any official document that is not issued by the state.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Mutilation (loss of extremities, branding), Up to 20 Years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing), and Confiscation of All Property (Except one weapon, one week's rations, and the offender's clothing worn at the time of sentencing.)

Slavery - The act of attempting or succeeding in the enslavement of any sentient creature for sale,
Appropriate Punishment:
- Up to 20 Years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing) and (if cruelty or physical indignities are observed) Mutilation.

Repetition of any Lesser or Minor Offense against Fellow Sentients
Appropriate Punishment: (Includes double the original sentence for previous offense)
- Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Up to 20 days Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Fine of Up to 1,000 GP and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Up to 1 Month Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Crimes against Religions

Theft of Temple Goods or Offerings - The act of stealing any item, goods and offerings, from a temple. Includes spoilage or consumption of goods.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Double the Estimated Value of the Goods, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Up to 1 Month Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Repetition of any Lesser or Minor Offense against Religions
Appropriate Punishment: (Includes double the original sentence for previous offense)
- Fine of Up to 200 GP and Up to 4 Months Imprisonment.

Lesser Offenses

Crimes against Crown & Country

Fraud - The act of attempting or succeeding in any deception to secure unfair or unlawful gain or to deprive a victim of legal rights.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Damages equal to what Justice Demands, Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Permanent Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
-Damages equal to what Justice Demands, Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Up To 20 Years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Unlawful Dueling (Manslaughter) - The act of killing another Citizen of Tethyr in an unlawful and unsanctioned duel or unintentionally killing another Citizen of Tethyr.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Damages Up to 1,000 GP and Up to 5 Years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
-Damages Up to 1,000 GP and Up to 3 Years Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Murder with Justification - The act of killing another Citizen of Tethyr with justification.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Up to 3 Years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
-Permanent Exile from Tethyr.

Unlawful Observation or Copying of an Official Document - The act of unlawfully observing or copying an official document.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Fine of 500 GP and 3 Weeks Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Assault Upon an Officer of the Realm Acting in the Line of Duty - The act of assaulting an officer of the realm while acting in the line of duty.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Fine of 50 GP and 1 Year of Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
-Fine as Justice Demands (Based on ability to pay) and 6 months Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Crimes against the People

Damage to Property - The act of willfully or unknowingly damaging another citizen of the realm's property that results in the property losing value.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Value of Goods Lost plus Up to 500 GP, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt).

Assault (Wounding) - The act of assaulting another Citizen of Tethyr that results in wounding.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Cost of Medical Attention plus Up to 50 GP, Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and 2 Days Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Assault (Without Wounding or Robbery) - The act of assaulting another Citizen of Tethyr that does not result in wounding.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to 25 GP and Up to 4 Days Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Blasphemy Against any Noble or Realm Officer - The act of slandering or speaking falsehoods of any noble or realm officer that would result in the defamation of their name.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine of up to 40 GP and Up to 6 Days Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Crimes against Religions

Assault Upon a Priest or Lay Worshipper - The act of assaulting any holy person or lay worshipper during worship.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Up to 500 GP, based on ability to pay, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), any additional punishments to those from "Defiling a Holy Place" as resulting from an assault.

Minor Offenses
Crimes against Crown & Country

Blasphemy Against Foreign Ambassadors or Royal Emissaries - The act of slandering or speaking falsehoods of any foreign ambassador, agent or emissary that would result in the defamation of their name.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine equal to Up to 50 GP, Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt), and Up to 10 Days Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Willful Disobedience of any Edict or Sentence - The act of willfully disobeying the lawful sentence of a Magistrate or disobeying an Edict issued by a Magistrate or another agent of the Court.
Appropriate Punishment:
-Fine equal to Up to 1,000 GP.
-Up to 5 Years Enforced Hard Labor (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Interference with Task of Any Realm Officer Acting in the Line of Duty - The act of willfully interrupting, stopping or preventing any Officer of the Realm from performing their duty.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt) and 2 Days Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).
- Fine equal to Up to 50 GP and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt).

Crimes against the People

Brandishing a Weapon without Due Cause - The act of displaying a weapon in a dangerous or threatening manner without being menaced with either spell or physical weapon.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Fine Equal to 4 GP, and Overnight Imprisonment (at a location of the Magistrate's choosing).

Excessive Noise - The act of generating excessive noise that interferes with sleep or business through any means.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Up to 10 GP, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt).

Crimes against Religion

Public Blasphemy of a Deity or Priesthood - The act of slandering or speaking falsehoods of any deity or priesthoods of a religion - regardless of creed, disposition or legality of worship. Includes the spread of blasphemous ideas such as Atheism or Monotheism.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Up to 10 GP, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt).

Drunkenness or Disorderly Conduct at Worship - The act of acting in a disorderly, disruptive, or drunken manner while at a place of worship.
Appropriate Punishment:
- Damages equal to Up to 5 GP, and Public Humiliation/Stocks/Edict Against Convicted (Including public pronouncement of guilt).

Lands of Intrigue Server Rules

Lands of Intrigue has both high integrity and high stakes. While not all players will participate in courtly intrigues, it can be expected that players will come into conflict with each other, and this is encouraged to a point.


Table of Contents:
1. Player Versus Player Encounters
2. Profanity
3. Sexual/Social Roleplay
4. Permadeath
5. Attacking Non-Hostile NPCs
6. Character Modifications
7. Item Transfer/Muling
8. Metagaming
9. Exploitation
10. Follow our discord rules, and use common sense


1. Player Versus Player Encounters
PVP involves two or more players doing battle with each other for any duration, whether the encounter is fatal or not.

The following behaviors in a PVP Encounter are considered to be fair game:

Looting dropped gold is allowed
Disarming an opponent of weaponry is allowed
Attacking another player without Out-Of-Character Consent is allowed
Moving a player's body to a hidden location is allowed
The following behaviors in a PVP Encounter are considered to be in poor taste:

Attacking an AFK character
Attacking others in front of NPCs
Ping-pong or repeated killings of the same player
Any form of exploit in PVP (transitions, etc)
Players do not have the ability to "closure" or "permakill" or "end" other player stories. You may defeat each other variously, you may sputter curses upon the grave of your foe. You can ride roads of the county singing about defeating them. But you may not send them OOC tells insisting that their character is not playable.  This judgment is reserved for DMs only.

2. Profanity
We have no problem with cursing/profanity, however we do suggest using more creative words.

3. Sexual/Social Roleplay
This is not an ERP server, so please go somewhere else if that is what you are looking for. Topics of Rape, Pedophilia, and full bestiality are grounds for an immediate and permanent ban.

4. Permanent Death
Permanent Death happens when a player has died and may no longer resurrect themselves via their own willpower (ie. the PC is above level 10). However, their corpse item still exists in-game and may be raised by someone else. It may be buried in a celebrated location or a secret one. Through player efforts, it is always possible to recover the remains of dead players and bring them back - if the magic to do so is powerful enough. A villain may be interred in the vault of a well-defended keep, meaning that manpower may be called for in addition to the favor of the gods.

5. Attacking Non-Hostile NPCs
Attacking Non-Hostile NPCs falls into two categories, doing so with a DM present, or not. While not prohibited, attacking and killing NPCs without DM supervision is done in poor taste. However, that is not to say that current intrigues do not justify the action, so it is preferred that a player with such designs contact a DM in order to portray the appropriate reaction on the part of the attacked NPCs.

6. Character Modifications
Re-leveling: Generally speaking, the DMs of the Lands of Intrigue server will allow you to re-take your last level without any hassle, assuming one is available. We will simply remove 1000 XP and give you 1000 XP back.
Alignment Changes: The DMs of the Lands of Intrigue server will allow you to make alignment changes as dictated by your desires for your character without any hassle. However, we reserve the right to adjust your alignment according to the actions of your character.
Head/Appearance Changes: These modifications are accessible in the Character Customization Room and require no permission to use.
Item Modification: We use MILs tailoring that has been modified to cost nothing to player characters, which is also accessible in the Character Customization Room.

7. Item Transfer/Muling
"Muling" items from one character to another is prohibited.

8. Metagaming
Metagaming is one of those age-old problems that is difficult to prove when it has transpired, so let's all be honest with each other and keep a firm separation between what is known in-character and out-of-character. If it seems like your character is always in the right place at the right time, we'll probably find a way to make your abuse of knowledge come around to haunt you. If you play more than one character, you may not share information between them, call them acquaintances, or any such thing. Playing two characters from the same family or who have some relation between each other is prohibited. 

9. Exploitation
Any activity that seriously compromises the game engine will result in a permanent CD-Key ban.

10. These as well as all rules ourlined in our discord's rules channel should be followed at all times. Pretty much use common sense and everything should be fine.

Rest System Overview

On the Lands of Intrigue server we have implemented a custom resting system. Please read all of the information below to have a better understanding of how Rest and Recovery works.

When can I rest?
Character Rest is limited by time. A character may rest in a comfortable bed every 2 in-game hours or every 1 real-life hour. A character may rest outside, but less often, once every 4 in-game hours or 2 real-life hours. Rest cannot take place unless the character is tired. If a character has become exhausted due to a weather effect they may rest independently of their rest timer. 

How do I recover HP from resting?
The amount of HP recovered from resting is based on character hit dice and constitution modifier, with additional benefits provided by resting in more comfortable beds.

If your character has Barbarian, Druid or Ranger classes or possesses the Survival Proficiency and is resting outside, they will receive High Quality rest.

High Quality rest provides 5d6 + level + Constitution modifier HP recovered
Medium Quality rest provides 4d6 + level + Constitution modifier HP recovered
Lower Quality rest provides 3d6 + level + Constitution modifier HP recovered
Resting outside with a bedroll provides 2d6 + level + Constitution modifier HP recovered
Resting outside without a bedroll provides 1d6 x level + Constitution HP recovered

Can I rest outside when it is raining?
Rest cannot take place under especially poor weather conditions. These include being too cold, too hot, too wet, or too windy. Using a tent will reduce these penalties and possibly enable rest. A better quality tent provides a better result. Survival Proficiency also allows a character to rest in less comfortable conditions and works with the benefit of a tent.

What else is there to know about resting?
Rest cannot take place in dungeons or in areas with enemies nearby.
Rest cannot take place while wearing armor, unless the character also possesses the Endurance Feat.
Rest cannot take place while poisoned or affected by a normal disease.
Rest is possible in a party if only one party member is resting at a time.
Resting Duration is 60 seconds, for which time a character is also blinded.

This bed has a beaten straw mattress, lined with well worn cotton sheets and covered with a worn woolen blanket.  Tended quite well, washed and scented, you will not find any bedbugs living here.  Soft enough to allow even the most hard adventurer a decent nights rest.

This book was a somewhat famous writing by an Ilmatari Painbearer, but was so old that his or her name was no longer attributed to the methods contained therein.

In this tale, a child with scuffed knees cries out in pain. Hearing this, the Painbearer suggested the use of a simple herb often recommended for treating heat-illness: humble garlic. By treating bandages with this essential substance, one could accelerate the normal course of recovery from injury. Most consider it a staple tale of Ilmater's priests easing suffering for any and all.

Creating Bandages:
Add a Hand of Garlic and Rags items into your Crafter's Box, and use the Combiner on the Crafting Box. Your check will be modified by your healing skill and relevant Backgrounds or Proficiencies. Each attempt will cost 2 gold.

Use: Bandages can only be used on unarmored creatures who are not in combat.

A holy symbol is the physical focus for the manifestation of a god's will.

As a follower of a specific deity there will be rites and practices associated with that deity. One thing that is common to all is the requirement to use the appropriate holy symbol when calling upon the deity's power. 

The Holy Symbol for each deity may be different and should be obtained from the appropriate temple. The holy symbol for a ranger or druid may be somthing sacred to the caster rather than a church sanctioned object.

This book contains a list of spells for which a practitioner must have a Holy Symbol equipped. 

In addition there are some spell which require other components. These are usually found in the same places arcane magic users obtain components.

This book is useful for Clerics, Druids, Rangers and Paladins.
